'''Mun Awng''' (born 1960)<ref name="Burmas forbudte sanger">{{cite web |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/kul_und/musikk/article2034262.ece |title=Burmas forbudte sanger |accessdate=2007-10-07 |publisher=Aftenposten.no}}</ref> is a Kachin singer, song writer, and pro-democracy activist. Awng was born in the Kachin State in north of [[Burma]] to a small [[Christian]] minority. His Christian name was Dennis Daws, a name he later changed. Awng became a popular singer and musician in Burma during the 1980s. Due to having participated in the wave of anti-government demonstrations in 1988, that resulted in more than 3,000 dead civilians, he was forced to leave Burma and has been living in exile in [[Eidsvoll]], [[Norway]] since.<ref name="Taunggyi">{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,235508,00.html |title=Hard Rock |accessdate=2007-10-07 |publisher=Time Magazine | date=2002-05-06 | first=PHIL ZABRISKIE | last=Taunggyi}}</ref> He fled to Norway to work with the opposition [[Democratic Voice of Burma]] radio and television broadcaster. From abroad he continued to release albums and activists sang his songs while facing down the military in both the 1996,<ref name="Taunggyi" /> and the [[2007 Burmese anti-government protests|2007 anti-government]]<ref name="Burmas forbudte sanger" /> street protests. Awng is considered a "subversive element" by the military junta in Burma.
==Music== Awng's music is a mix of Western style rock music and east Asian ballads.<ref name="Burmas forbudte sanger"/> Since he flew into exile he has not produced more than two albums in the last fourteen years. Even under the scrutiny of the notorious censorship board, the [[Press Scrutiny and Registration Division|Press Scrutiny Board]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=2707 |title=And The Band Played On |accessdate=2007-10-07 |publisher=The irrawaddy |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803105654/http://www.irrawaddy.org/article.php?art_id=2707 |archivedate=2010-08-03 |df= }}</ref> Awng managed to produce one album a year in Burma.<ref name="Taunggyi"/> He occasionally performs his music for Burmese exiles in other countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theworld.org/?q=taxonomy_by_date/2/20071004 |title=PRI's The World - Burmese musicians |accessdate=2007-10-07 |publisher=PRI}}</ref>
==For The Lady== In 2004 Awng was part of a musical project to raise funds for the [[U.S. Campaign for Burma|US campaign for Democracy in Burma]]. Together with well-known pop stars such as [[U2]], [[Avril Lavigne]], [[Talib Kweli]] and more they created an album dedicated to the famous Burmese [[democracy]] activist [[Aung San Suu Kyi]]. Awng penned the album's final cut with his "Tempest of Blood".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/burmese/highlights/story/2004/11/041101_for_the_lady.shtml |title=For The Lady |accessdate=2007-10-07 |publisher=BBC Burmese |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050309202649/http://www.bbc.co.uk/burmese/highlights/story/2004/11/041101_for_the_lady.shtml |archivedate=2005-03-09 |df= }}</ref>
